  Part A — Manual steps (you do these, ~10–15 minutes)

1. Create a Resend account — go to resend.com, sign up with email/password. No credit card needed for the free tier.

2. Decide on domain verification now vs. later

Fastest path for beta testing: skip domain verification for now and send from Resend's default onboarding@resend.dev address. Important caveat: without a verified domain, Resend only lets you send to the email address you signed up with — not to arbitrary tester emails. That's fine if you're the one clicking every magic link during dev, but it won't work once real testers try to log in with their own emails.
Better path if you have any domain already (even a cheap one you're not using yet, or a subdomain of your main site): verify it now, since you'll need it anyway once testers are real people. Steps: in the Resend dashboard, go to Domains → Add Domain, enter your domain, and Resend gives you a few DNS records (usually SPF, DKIM, and sometimes a tracking/return-path record). Add those records wherever your DNS is managed (Cloudflare, GoDaddy, Namecheap, etc.), then click Verify DNS Records in Resend. This can take a few minutes to a few hours to propagate depending on your DNS provider.
I'd verify a domain now — even a throwaway subdomain like mail.yourdomain.com — since the "only send to yourself" limitation will block your actual beta test otherwise.

3. Create an API key — in the dashboard, go to API Keys → Create API Key, give it a name like "Verve backend," and set permission to Sending access (scoped to your domain once verified, if you want to restrict it). Copy the key immediately — Resend only shows it once.

4. Save the key somewhere safe — you'll drop it into your backend's .env file (not committed to git) in the next part.

